%pylab inline
import requests
import pandas
import json
%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'
password = open('./password.txt', 'r').read().strip()
auth=('eoinmurray', password)
## Growth rate of number of repos on Github

data = json.loads(open('./data/id_vs_date.json', 'r').read())
df = pandas.DataFrame(data, columns=['created_at', 'id', 'name', 'url'])
df['created_at'] = pandas.to_datetime(df['created_at'])
df.sort_values(by='created_at')
df.set_index('created_at');

group = df['id'].groupby(df.created_at.dt.year)
all_repos = group.max()

all_repos = all_repos.drop(all_repos.index[[0, 1]])

print(all_repos)

p = all_repos.plot(kind="bar", figsize=(8, 4))
p.set_title('Total number of repos on Github')

### Searching the API

We search where we sort descending by the number of stars.

store = []

for page in range(1, 30):
    r = requests.get('https://api.github.com/search/repositories?q=data+science&sort=stars&page=%s'% page, auth=auth)
    store.append(r.json()['items'])

flat = [item for sublist in store for item in sublist]

with open('data/search_star_desc.json', 'w') as outfile:
    json.dump(flat, outfile)
### Now lets process the data

data_stars = json.loads(open('./data/search_star_desc.json', 'r').read())
df_stars = pandas.DataFrame(data_stars, columns=['created_at', 'name', 'stargazers_count', 'description'])

df_stars['created_at'] = pandas.to_datetime(df_stars['created_at'])
df_stars.set_index('created_at');
Lets group the data by the number of stars - pandas will automatically group for us.
grouped_stars = df_stars['stargazers_count'].groupby(df_stars.created_at.dt.year)

### Median stars per repo per year

Default search results:

p = grouped_stars.median().plot(kind="line", figsize=(8, 4))
p.set_title('Median number of stars for repos matching data-science per year')
p.set_xlim(xmin=2012)

p = grouped_stars.count().cumsum().plot(kind="line", figsize=(8, 4))
p.set_title('Count of repos matching data-science per year')
p.set_xlim(xmin=2012)

### Popularity adjusted number of repos per year

Assumption: 

> Repos made every year are of the same quality and relevance - thus
> the average stars per repo should tend to equality as time goes on

Since older repos have more time to get more stars - it will scew the search results. 
Lets normalise then the number of repos per year by the average stars per year.

normed_stars = grouped_stars.count().cumsum()/grouped_stars.median()
p = normed_stars.plot(kind="line", figsize=(8, 4))
p.set_title('Popularity adjusted count of repos matching data-science per year')
p.set_xlim(xmin=2012)

normed_stars = grouped_stars.count().cumsum()/(grouped_stars.median())
p = normed_stars.plot(kind="line", figsize=(8, 4))
p.set_title('Popularity adjusted count of repos matching data-science per year')
p.set_xlim(xmin=2012)
normed_stars = grouped_stars.count().cumsum()/(grouped_stars.median())
real_repos = 160*normed_stars/(all_repos/5e5)

p = real_repos.plot(kind="line", figsize=(8, 4))
p.set_xlim(xmin=2012)
p.set_title('Count of repos matching data-science per year normalized by total number of repos')
## Google trends data

google_data = pandas.read_csv('./data/multiTimeline.csv')
google_data['date'] = pandas.to_datetime(google_data['date'])
google_data.set_index('date', inplace=True)
p = (google_data/google_data.max()).plot(figsize=(8, 4))
p.set_title('Google trends for the phrase "data-science"')
